{"title_page": "Life of Despot Stefan Lazarevi\u0107", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{Expand Serbian|\u0416\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u0434\u0435\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0442\u0430 \u0421\u0442\u0435\u0444\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u041b\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b\u0430|date=March 2017}}\nThe '''''Life of Despot Stefan Lazarevi\u0107''''' ({{lang-sr|\u0416\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0442 \u0434\u0435\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0442\u0430 \u0421\u0442\u0435\u0444\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u041b\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b\u0430, \u0416\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u0434\u0435\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0442\u0430 \u0421\u0442\u0435\u0444\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u041b\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b\u0430}}) is a biography of Serbian ruler [[Stefan Lazarevi\u0107]] authored by [[Constantine of Kostenets]] (\"the Philosopher\") ca. 1431. The biography had been ordered by Serbian Patriarch Nikon following the death of Despot Stefan. That order was only fulfilled four years later, when allegedly Despot Stefan himself appeared in Constantine's dream. The biography is regarded as one of the most interesting in the [[medieval Serbian literature]] because it contains not only facts about the Despot's life, but also geographic information and thorough descriptions of numerous historical events. Constantine was apparently inspired by Byzantine chronicles. The work begins with a geographic description of Serbia's natural beauties, going on to describe its residents, praising their character but also mourning their forthcoming fall to the Turks. An exhaustive story of court events and Despot Stefan's life follows, with numerous Biblical and classical references and numerous historical data which have proven invaluable to later historians. On several occasions, Constantine used [[acrostic]]s, with three masterpiece instances: in the introduction verses, in the titles of central chapters, and in the verses telling of his sorrow for the deceased.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Life of Stefan Nemanja]]\n*[[Life of St. Sava (by Domentijan)]]\n*[[Life of St. Sava (by Teodosije)]]\n\n==References==\n;Books\n*''Life of Despot Stefan Lazarevi\u0107'' by [[Constantine of Kostenets|Constantine the Philosopher]] (ca. 1431).\n**{{cite book|editor=Braun, Maximilian|title=Lebensbeschreibung des Despoten Stefan Lazarevi\u0107|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FoY6AQAAIAAJ|year=1956|publisher=Mouton}}\n**{{cite book|translator=Mirkovi\u0107, L.|title=\u0416\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0442 \u0434\u0435\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0442\u0430 \u0421\u0442\u0435\u0444\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u041b\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b\u0430|work=\u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0435 \u0441\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0435 \u0431\u0438\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0458\u0435 XV \u0438 XVII \u0432\u0435\u043a\u0430|year=1936|publisher=\u0421\u041a\u0417}}\n**{{cite journal|editor=Jagi\u0107, V.|title=\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d \u0424\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0437\u043e\u0444, \u201e\u0416\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0442 \u0421\u0442\u0435\u0444\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u041b\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b\u0430\u201c|journal=\u0413\u043b\u0430\u0441\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0421\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433 \u0443\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0433 \u0434\u0440\u0443\u0448\u0442\u0432\u0430|volume=42|year=1875|pp=223\u2013328|url=https://archive.org/stream/glasniks42srpsuoft#page/223/}}\n\n;Journals\n*{{cite journal|last=Kotseva|first=Elena|title=The Virtues of the Ruler according to the Life of Stefan Lazarevi\u0107 by Constantine of Kostenets|journal=Scripta & e-Scripta|volume=13|year=2014|pp=123-129}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Mihailovi\u0107-Milo\u0161evi\u0107|first=S.|year=2012|title=Literary character of the Despot Stefan Lazarevi\u0107 in The Lives of Constantine Philosopher|journal=Ba\u0161tina|issue=32|pages=41\u201349|url=http://scindeks-clanci.ceon.rs/data/pdf/0353-9008/2012/0353-90081232041M.pdf}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Ristovi\u0107|first=Nenad|title=Aspects of reception of classical heritage in biography of despot Stefan Lazarevi\u0107 of Constantine the Philosopher|journal=Zbornik radova Vizantolo\u0161kog instituta|volume=48|year=2011|pp=287-306}}\n\n[[Category:Medieval Serbian literature]]\n[[Category:15th century in Serbia]]\n[[Category:1430s books]]\n[[Category:Serbian Despotate]]\n[[Category:Lazarevi\u0107 dynasty]]\n[[Category:History of the Serbian Orthodox Church]]\n[[Category:Books about monarchs]]\n[[Category:15th-century history books]]\n[[Category:Serbian manuscripts]]\n[[Category:Cyrillic manuscripts]]\n[[Category:Christian hagiography]]\n[[Category:1431]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{Expand Serbian|\u0416\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u0434\u0435\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0442\u0430 \u0421\u0442\u0435\u0444\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u041b\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b\u0430|date=March 2017}}\nThe '''Life of Despot Stefan Lazarevi\u0107''' ({{lang-sr|\u0416\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0442 \u0434\u0435\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0442\u0430 \u0421\u0442\u0435\u0444\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u041b\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b\u0430, \u0416\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u0434\u0435\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0442\u0430 \u0421\u0442\u0435\u0444\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u041b\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b\u0430}}) is a biography on Serbian ruler [[Stefan Lazarevi\u0107]], authored by [[Constantine of Kostenets]] (\"the Philosopher\") in ca. 1431. The biography had been ordered by Serbian Patriarch Nikon following the death of Despot Stefan. That order was only fulfilled four years later, when allegedly Despot Stefan himself appeared in Constantine's dream. The biography is regarded one of the most interesting in the [[medieval Serbian literature]] because it contains not only facts about the Despot's life, but also geographic information and thorough descriptions of numerous historical events. Constantine was apparently inspired by Byzantine chronicles. The work begins with a geographic description of Serbia's natural beauties, going on to describe its residents, praising their character but also mourning their forthcoming fall to the Turks. An exhaustive story of court events and Despot Stefan's life follows, with numerous Biblical and classical references, as well with numerous historical data which have proven invaluable to later historians. On several occasions, Constantine used [[acrostic]]s, with three masterpiece instances: in the introduction verses, in the titles of central chapters, and finally, in the verses telling of his sorrow for the deceased.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Life of Stefan Nemanja]]\n*[[Life of St. Sava (by Domentijan)]]\n*[[Life of St. Sava (by Teodosije)]]\n\n==References==\n;Books\n*''Life of Despot Stefan Lazarevi\u0107'' by [[Constantine of Kostenets|Constantine the Philosopher]] (ca. 1431).\n**{{cite book|editor=Braun, Maximilian|title=Lebensbeschreibung des Despoten Stefan Lazarevi\u0107|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FoY6AQAAIAAJ|year=1956|publisher=Mouton}}\n**{{cite book|translator=Mirkovi\u0107, L.|title=\u0416\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0442 \u0434\u0435\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0442\u0430 \u0421\u0442\u0435\u0444\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u041b\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b\u0430|work=\u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0435 \u0441\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0435 \u0431\u0438\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0458\u0435 XV \u0438 XVII \u0432\u0435\u043a\u0430|year=1936|publisher=\u0421\u041a\u0417}}\n**{{cite journal|editor=Jagi\u0107, V.|title=\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d \u0424\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0437\u043e\u0444, \u201e\u0416\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0442 \u0421\u0442\u0435\u0444\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u041b\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b\u0430\u201c|journal=\u0413\u043b\u0430\u0441\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0421\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433 \u0443\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0433 \u0434\u0440\u0443\u0448\u0442\u0432\u0430|volume=42|year=1875|pp=223\u2013328|ur